<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-329-632  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 329 632.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Newsbytes  April 7 1990* Full Text COPYRIGHT Newsbytes Inc. 1990.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>MITI offers guidelines against computer viruses. (Japan. Ministryof International Trade and Industry)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Yazawa, Naoyuki.andM;</AUTHOR><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Computer industryComputer virusesSecurityGuidelinesAccess ControlsReportsGovernment Agency.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>MITI OFFERS GUIDELINES AGAINST COMPUTER VIRUSES TOKYO, JAPAN, 1990 MAR 30(NB) -- An advisory panel to the Ministry of International Trade and Industryor MITI has drafted guidelines to battle computer viruses.andP;  The guidelinesare expected to be finalized and publicized before Friday the 13th, of Aprilthis year.andM;The guideline covers everything from personal computers to general purposecomputers and is designed for users, system managers and software developers.andO;The three parts of the guideline consist of 59 items: 19 items for users,include a how-to on passwords secrecy; 27 items for system managers,including regular data back-up; and 13 items for software developers,including methods to prevent unauthorized access through public telephonelines.andM;MITI also requests that readers report a virus infection to the Information-technology of Promotion Agency (IPA) when their computers are infected inorder to prevent widespread proliferation of the viruses and to developvaccine programs.andM;(Naoyuki Yazawa/19900405/Press Contact: Information-technology PromotionAgency, 03-437-2301)</TEXT></DOC>